Explainer None
Specification &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://w3c.github.io/push-api/#the-pushsubscriptionchange-event"&gt;https://w3c.github.io/push-api/#the-pushsubscriptionchange-event&lt;/a&gt;
Summary
Fire the pushsubscriptionchange event in service workers when an origin for which a push subscription existed in the past, but which was revoked because of a permission change (from granted to deny/default), is re-granted notification permission. The event will be fired with an empty oldSubscription and newSubscription.
Blink component Blink&gt;PushAPI
TAG review None
TAG review status Not applicable
Risks
Interoperability and Compatibility
None
Gecko: Shipped/Shipping (&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1497429"&gt;https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1497429&lt;/a&gt;) Firefox seems to already implement a similar behavior, see &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1497429"&gt;https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1497429&lt;/a&gt;
WebKit: No signal Seems shipped, but couldn't figure out the exact details. See &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/ServiceWorkerGlobalScope/pushsubscriptionchange_event"&gt;https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/ServiceWorkerGlobalScope/pushsubscriptionchange_event&lt;/a&gt;
Web developers: No signals Likely positive, see for example &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://issues.chromium.org/issues/40129474"&gt;https://issues.chromium.org/issues/40129474&lt;/a&gt;
